IPFS(8)                                                   IPFS(8)



NNAAMMEE
       ipfs  -  saves  and restores information for NAT and state
       tables.

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       iippffss [-nv] -l

       iippffss [-nv] -u

       iippffss [-nv] [ --dd <_d_i_r_n_a_m_e> ] -R

       iippffss [-nv] [ --dd <_d_i_r_n_a_m_e> ] -W

       iippffss [-nNSv] [ --ff <_f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e> ] -r

       iippffss [-nNSv] [ --ff <_f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e> ] -w

       iippffss [-nNSv] --ff <_f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e> --ii <if1>,<if2>

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       iippffss allows state information created for NAT entries  and
       rules  using  _k_e_e_p  _s_t_a_t_e  to be locked (modification pre-
       vented) and then saved to disk, allowing for the system to
       experience  a  reboot, followed by the restoration of that
       information, resulting in  connections  not  being  inter-
       rupted.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --dd     Change  the  default  directory used with --RR and --WW
              options for saving state information.

       --nn     Don't actually take any action  that  would  effect
              information stored in the kernel or on disk.

       --vv     Provides  a  verbose  description  of  what's being
              done.

       --ii <<iiffnnaammee11>>,,<<iiffnnaammee22>>
              Change all instances of interface name  ifname1  in
              the  state  save file to ifname2.  Useful if you're
              restoring state information after a hardware recon-
              figuration or change.

       --NN     Operate on NAT information.

       --SS     Operate on filtering state information.

       --uu     Unlock state tables in the kernel.

       --ll     Lock state tables in the kernel.

       --rr     Read  information  in  from  the specified file and
              load it into the kernel.  This requires  the  state
              tables  to  have  already  been locked and does not
              change the lock once comlete.

       --ww     Write information out to  the  specified  file  and
              from the kernel.  This requires the state tables to
              have already been locked and does  not  change  the
              lock once comlete.

       --RR     Restores  all saved state information, if any, from
              two files, _i_p_s_t_a_t_e_._i_p_f and _i_p_n_a_t_._i_p_f, stored in the
              _/_v_a_r_/_d_b_/_i_p_f  directory  unless  otherwise specified
              the --dd option is used.  The state tables are locked
              at  the  beginning  of  this operation and unlocked
              once complete.

       --WW     Saves in-kernel state information, if any,  out  to
              two files, _i_p_s_t_a_t_e_._i_p_f and _i_p_n_a_t_._i_p_f, stored in the
              _/_v_a_r_/_d_b_/_i_p_f directory  unless  otherwise  specified
              the --dd option is used.  The state tables are locked
              at the beginning of  this  operation  and  unlocked
              once complete.

FFIILLEESS
       /var/db/ipf/ipstate.ipf
       /var/db/ipf/ipnat.ipf
       /dev/ipl
       /dev/ipstate
       /dev/ipnat

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ipf(8), ipl(4), ipmon(8), ipnat(8)

DDIIAAGGNNOOSSTTIICCSS
       Perhaps  the  -W  and -R operations should set the locking
       but rather than undo it, restore it to what it was  previ-
       ously.  Fragment table information is currently not saved.

BBUUGGSS
       If  you  find  any,  please  send  email  to  me  at  dar-
       renr@pobox.com



